{"title_page": "Lilium bulbiferum", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = Lilium bulbiferum var. bulbiferum 01.JPG\n| genus = Lilium\n| species = bulbiferum\n| authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|L.]] 1753 not Thunb. 1794\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=uy>{{cite web|url=http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/synonomy.do?name_id=280683|title=World Checklist of Selected Plant Families: Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref>\n| synonyms =\n{{collapsible list|bullets = true\n|title=<small>Synonymy</small>\n|''Lilium chaixii'' <small> Maw</small>\n|''Lilium aurantiacum'' <small> Weston</small>\n|''Lilium croceum'' <small> Chaix</small>\n|''Lilium pubescens'' <small> Bernh. ex Hornem.</small>\n|''Lilium humile'' <small> Mill., 1768</small>\n|''Lilium scabrum'' <small> Moench, 1794</small>\n|''Lilium aurantiacum'' <small> Weston, 1771</small>\n|''Lilium luteum'' <small> Gaterau, 1789</small>\n|''Lilium elatum'' <small>Salisb.</small>\n|''Lilium sibiricum'' <small>Willd.</small>\n|''Lilium latifolium'' <small>Link</small> \n|''Lilium fulgens'' <small>W.H.Baxter</small>\n|''Lilium sanguineum'' <small>Lindl.</small>\n|''Lilium fulgens'' <small>E.Morren ex Spae</small>\n|''Lilium haematochroum'' <small>Lem.</small>\n|''Lilium atrosanguineum'' <small>H.Vilm.</small>\n|''Lilium biligulatum'' <small>Baker</small>\n|''Lilium lateritium'' <small>Baker</small>\n|''Lilium pictum'' <small>Baker</small>\n|plus many names at the [[Variety (botany)|varietal]] level\n}}}}\n\n'''''Lilium bulbiferum''''', common names '''orange lily''',<ref>{{PLANTS|id=LIBU|taxon=Lilium bulbiferum|accessdate=25 January 2016}}</ref> '''fire lily''' and '''tiger lily''', is a  [[herbaceous]] European lily with underground bulbs, belonging to the [[Liliaceae]].<ref name=uy/><ref name=yu/>\n\nThe Latin name ''bulbiferum'' of this species, meaning \"bearing bulbs\", refers to the secondary bulbs on the stem of the nominal subspecies.\n\n==Description==\n''Lilium bulbiferum'' reaches on average {{convert|20|-|90|cm}} of height, with a maximum of  {{convert|120|cm}}. The bulbs are ovoid, with whitish large and pointed scales and can reach about {{convert|1.5|cm}} of diameter. The stem is erect, the leaves are lanceolate, up to 10 centimeters long. The inflorescence has one to five short-haired flowers. They are hermaphroditic and scentless, have six upright [[tepal]]s, the outer are slightly narrower than the inner ones. The flowers can reach 4\u20136 centimeters in length and are bright yellow-orange with reddish-brown dots. The [[stamen]]s are erect, about half as long as the [[tepal]]s, with red [[anther]]s. The style is orange, {{convert|35|mm}} of height. The flowering period extends from May through July.<ref>Pignatti S. - Flora d'Italia - Edagricole \u2013 1982 Vol. III. pa. 362</ref>\n\nThere are two varieties, ''L. b.'' var. ''croceum'' <small>(Chaix) Baker</small> in the western part of the range, and ''L. b.'' var. ''bulbiferum'' in its eastern part. Only the last one always produces secondary aerial bulbs (''bulbils'') in the axils of the upper leaves.  These ''bulbils'' fall to the ground and mature after two to three years. When manually separated from the stem they can easily used for propagating the plant.\n\nThe dwarf plants from the [[Maritime Alps]], formerly described as var. ''chaixii'' <small>(Elwes) Stoker</small>, and the large plants from the region of [[Naples]], formerly described as var. ''giganteum'' <small>N. Terracc.</small>, are now considered as local variants of var. ''croceum''.\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\n''L. bulbiferum'' is widely distributed in much of Europe from Spain to Finland and [[Ukraine]].<ref name=yu>[http://luirig.altervista.org/flora/taxa/index1.php?scientific-name=lilium+bulbiferum Altervista Flora Italiana, Giglio rosso, Orange Lily, ''Lilium bulbiferum'' L.] includes many photos plus European distribution map</ref> It grows in mountain meadows and on hillsides. They prefer calcareous soils in warm, sunny places, but also grow on slightly acid soils. They can be found at an altitude of {{convert|500|-|1900|m}} above sea level.\n\n==In culture==\nThe orange lily has long been recognised as a symbol of the [[Orange Order]] in [[Northern Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://designresearchgroup.wordpress.com/2007/06/27/a-kinder-gentler-image-modernism-tradition-and-the-orange-order-redesign/|title=A kinder gentler image? Modernism, Tradition and the new Orange Order logo.|first=Reinventing the Orange Order: A. superhero for the 21st century \u00ab Design Research Group 12 12 07 /|last=8pm|date=27 June 2007|publisher=|accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Toxicity==\n\n===Cats===\n[[Cats]] are extremely sensitive to lily toxicity and ingestion is often fatal;<ref>[http://www.noliliesforcats.com/faq1.pml Frequently Asked Questions] No Lilies For Cats.</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 21147474 | doi=10.1053/j.tcam.2010.09.006 | volume=25 | title=Lily toxicity in the cat | year=2010 | journal=Top hCompanion Anim Med | pages=213\u20137 | last1 = Fitzgerald | first1 = KT}}</ref><ref>[http://www.petpoisonhelpline.com/poison/tiger-lily/ Tiger Lilly] Pet Poison Helpline.</ref> households and gardens which are visited by cats are strongly advised against keeping this plant or placing dried flowers where a cat may brush against them and become dusted with pollen which they then consume while cleaning.<ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2289569/The-Valentine-bouquet-killed-cats-Mothers-Day-warning-lethal-lilies.html The Valentine bouquet that killed my cats: Mother's Day warning on lethal lilies] ''Daily Mail''.</ref> Suspected cases require urgent veterinary attention.<ref name=\"petmd\" /> Rapid treatment with [[activated charcoal]] or induced [[vomiting]] can reduce the amount of toxin absorbed (this is time-sensitive so in some cases veterinarians may advise doing it at home), and large amounts of fluid by [[Intravenous injection|IV]] can reduce damage to kidneys to increase the chances of survival.<ref name=\"petmd\">[http://www.petmd.com/cat/emergency/poisoning-toxicity/e_ct_lily_poisoning Lily Poisoning in Cats]. Pet MD.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q163766}}\n\n[[Category:Lilium|bulbiferum]]\n[[Category:Flora of Europe]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1753]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = Lilium bulbiferum var. bulbiferum 01.JPG\n| genus = Lilium\n| species = bulbiferum\n| authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|L.]] 1753 not Thunb. 1794\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=uy>{{cite web|url=http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/synonomy.do?name_id=280683|title=World Checklist of Selected Plant Families: Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref>\n| synonyms =\n{{collapsible list|bullets = true\n|title=<small>Synonymy</small>\n|''Lilium chaixii'' <small> Maw</small>\n|''Lilium aurantiacum'' <small> Weston</small>\n|''Lilium croceum'' <small> Chaix</small>\n|''Lilium pubescens'' <small> Bernh. ex Hornem.</small>\n|''Lilium humile'' <small> Mill., 1768</small>\n|''Lilium scabrum'' <small> Moench, 1794</small>\n|''Lilium aurantiacum'' <small> Weston, 1771</small>\n|''Lilium luteum'' <small> Gaterau, 1789</small>\n|''Lilium elatum'' <small>Salisb.</small>\n|''Lilium sibiricum'' <small>Willd.</small>\n|''Lilium latifolium'' <small>Link</small> \n|''Lilium fulgens'' <small>W.H.Baxter</small>\n|''Lilium sanguineum'' <small>Lindl.</small>\n|''Lilium fulgens'' <small>E.Morren ex Spae</small>\n|''Lilium haematochroum'' <small>Lem.</small>\n|''Lilium atrosanguineum'' <small>H.Vilm.</small>\n|''Lilium biligulatum'' <small>Baker</small>\n|''Lilium lateritium'' <small>Baker</small>\n|''Lilium pictum'' <small>Baker</small>\n|plus many names at the [[Variety (botany)|varietal]] level\n}}}}\n\n'''''Lilium bulbiferum''''', common names '''orange lily''',<ref>{{PLANTS|id=LIBU|taxon=Lilium bulbiferum|accessdate=25 January 2016}}</ref> '''fire lily''' and '''tiger lily''', is a  [[herbaceous]] European lily with underground bulbs, belonging to the [[Liliaceae]].<ref name=uy/><ref name=yu/>\n\nThe Latin name ''bulbiferum'' of this species, meaning \"bearing bulbs\", refers to the secondary bulbs on the stem of the nominal subspecies.\n\n==Description==\n''Lilium bulbiferum'' reaches on average {{convert|20|-|90|cm}} of height, with a maximum of  {{convert|120|cm}}. The bulbs are ovoid, with whitish large and pointed scales and can reach about {{convert|1.5|cm}} of diameter. The stem is erect, the leaves are lanceolate, up to 10 centimeters long. The inflorescence has one to five short-haired flowers. They are hermaphroditic and scentless, have six upright [[tepal]]s, the outer are slightly narrower than the inner ones. The flowers can reach 4\u20136 centimeters in length and are bright yellow-orange with reddish-brown dots. The [[stamen]]s are erect, about half as long as the [[tepal]]s, with red [[anther]]s. The style is orange, {{convert|35|mm}} of height. The flowering period extends from May through July.<ref>Pignatti S. - Flora d'Italia - Edagricole \u2013 1982 Vol. III. pa. 362</ref>\n\nThere are two varieties, ''L. b.'' var. ''croceum'' <small>(Chaix) Baker</small> in the western part of the range, and ''L. b.'' var. ''bulbiferum'' in its eastern part. Only the last one always produces secondary aerial bulbs (''bulbils'') in the axils of the upper leaves.  These ''bulbils'' fall to the ground and mature after two to three years. When manually separated from the stem they can easily used for propagating the plant.\n\nThe dwarf plants from the [[Maritime Alps]], formerly described as var. ''chaixii'' <small>(Elwes) Stoker</small>, and the large plants from the region of [[Naples]], formerly described as var. ''giganteum'' <small>N. Terracc.</small>, are now considered as local variants of var. ''croceum''.\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\n''L. bulbiferum'' is widely distributed in much of Europe from Spain to Finland and [[Ukraine]].<ref name=yu>[http://luirig.altervista.org/flora/taxa/index1.php?scientific-name=lilium+bulbiferum Altervista Flora Italiana, Giglio rosso, Orange Lily, ''Lilium bulbiferum'' L.] includes many photos plus European distribution map</ref> It grows in mountain meadows and on hillsides. They prefer calcareous soils in warm, sunny places, but also grow on slightly acid soils. They can be found at an altitude of {{convert|500|-|1900|m}} above sea level.\n\n==In culture==\nThe orange lily has long been recognised as a symbol of the [[Orange Order]] in [[Northern Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://designresearchgroup.wordpress.com/2007/06/27/a-kinder-gentler-image-modernism-tradition-and-the-orange-order-redesign/|title=A kinder gentler image? Modernism, Tradition and the new Orange Order logo.|first=Reinventing the Orange Order: A. superhero for the 21st century \u00ab Design Research Group 12 12 07 /|last=8pm|date=27 June 2007|publisher=|accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Toxicity==\n\n===Cats===\n[[Cats]] are extremely sensitive to lily toxicity and ingestion is often fatal;<ref>[http://www.noliliesforcats.com/faq1.pml Frequently Asked Questions] No Lilies For Cats.</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 21147474 | doi=10.1053/j.tcam.2010.09.006 | volume=25 | title=Lily toxicity in the cat | year=2010 | journal=Top Companion Anim Med | pages=213\u20137 | last1 = Fitzgerald | first1 = KT}}</ref><ref>[http://www.petpoisonhelpline.com/poison/tiger-lily/ Tiger Lilly] Pet Poison Helpline.</ref> households and gardens which are visited by cats are strongly advised against keeping this plant or placing dried flowers where a cat may brush against them and become dusted with pollen which they then consume while cleaning.<ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2289569/The-Valentine-bouquet-killed-cats-Mothers-Day-warning-lethal-lilies.html The Valentine bouquet that killed my cats: Mother's Day warning on lethal lilies] ''Daily Mail''.</ref> Suspected cases require urgent veterinary attention.<ref name=\"petmd\" /> Rapid treatment with [[activated charcoal]] or induced [[vomiting]] can reduce the amount of toxin absorbed (this is time-sensitive so in some cases veterinarians may advise doing it at home), and large amounts of fluid by [[Intravenous injection|IV]] can reduce damage to kidneys to increase the chances of survival.<ref name=\"petmd\">[http://www.petmd.com/cat/emergency/poisoning-toxicity/e_ct_lily_poisoning Lily Poisoning in Cats]. Pet MD.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q163766}}\n\n[[Category:Lilium|bulbiferum]]\n[[Category:Flora of Europe]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1753]]\n", "name_user": "174.57.15.68", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eToxicity)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lilium_bulbiferum"}
{"title_page": "Please Sir!", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2014}}\n{{Refimprove|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox television\n | image = Please_Sir!_(TV_series).jpg\n | caption = Opening title card\n | show_name = Please Sir!\n | runtime = 25-45 minutes\n | creator =  \n | starring = [[John Alderton]]<br />[[Deryck Guyler]]<br />[[Noel Howlett]]<br />[[Joan Sanderson]]<br />[[Richard Davies (actor)|Richard Davies]]<br />[[Erik Chitty]]<br />[[David Barry (actor)|David Barry]]<br />[[Peter Cleall]]<br />[[Peter Denyer]]<br />[[Liz Gebhardt]]<br />[[Malcolm McFee]]<br />[[Penny Spencer]]<br />[[Carol Hawkins]]<br />[[Richard Warwick]] \n | country = United Kingdom\n | language = English\n | picture_format = [[4:3]]\n | audio_format = [[Monaural|Mono]]\n| theme_music_composer     = [[Sam Fonteyn]]\n| opentheme                = \"School's Out\"\n| endtheme                 = \n | company = [[London Weekend Television]]\n | distributor = [[ITV Studios]]\n | network = [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n | first_aired = {{Start date|1968|11|8|df=y}}\n | last_aired = {{End date|1972|2|12|df=y}}\n | num_series  = 4\n | num_episodes = 55\n | related = ''[[The Fenn Street Gang]]''\n}}\n'''''Please Sir!''''' is a [[London Weekend Television]] [[situation comedy]] for [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]], created by [[Esmonde and Larbey|John Esmonde]] and [[Esmonde and Larbey|Bob Larbey]] and featuring actors [[John Alderton]], [[Deryck Guyler]], [[Penny Spencer]], [[Joan Sanderson]], [[Noel Howlett]], [[Erik Chitty]] and [[Richard Davies (actor)|Richard Davies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.televisionheaven.co.uk/pleasesir.htm |title=Please Sir! &#124; A Television Heaven Review |website=Televisionheaven.co.uk |date=1972-02-13 |accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref> The series ran for 55 episodes between 1968 and 1972.<ref name=comedy>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.sitcom.co.uk/please_sir/index.shtml |title=Please Sir! - ITV Sitcom - British Comedy Guide |website=Sitcom.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref>\n\nThe theme tune \"School's Out\" was by [[Sam Fonteyn]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=44ElLnnG_Tg|title=Top TV Soundtrack Themes. Please Sir|first=|last=bishdaboo|date=9 October 2011|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0067591/soundtrack|title=Please Sir! (1971)|publisher=www.imdb.com}|accessdate=8 January 2018}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nThe programme was set in the fictional Fenn Street Secondary Modern School, and starred John Alderton as Bernard Hedges, a young teacher fresh out of training college.<ref name=comedy/> The supporting cast included Deryck Guyler, Joan Sanderson and Richard Davies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nostalgiacentral.com/television/tv-by-decade/tv-shows-1960s/please-sir/|title=Please, Sir! - Nostalgia Central|website=nostalgiacentral.com}}</ref> Character actors and actresses formed the guest cast, including [[Mollie Sugden]] as a parent of one of the pupils, [[Barbara Mitchell]] as Frankie Abbott's mother, and [[Ann Lancaster]] as Mrs Pearce in a pair of 1968 episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b847eecda|title=What&#039;s a Class between Friends (1971)|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/please_sir/episodes/2/3/|title=Please Sir! Series 2, Episode 3 - Panalal Passes By - British Comedy Guide|first=British Comedy|last=Guide|website=British Comedy Guide}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b84787f82|title=A Near Greek Tragedy (1968)|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6b2efc81|title=Maureen Bullock Loves Sir (1968)|publisher=}}</ref>.\n\nBernard Hedges and the 5C pupils were replaced by a new teacher and pupils for the final series in 1971\u201372, while the original pupils continued in a spin-off series, ''[[The Fenn Street Gang]]'', which ran for 47 episodes between 1971 and 1972.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sitcom.co.uk/fenn_street/ |title=British Comedy Guide - The Fenn Street Gang |website=Sitcom.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref> This was followed by ''[[Bowler (TV series)|Bowler]]'' (1973), following crime boss Stanley Bowler, played by [[George Baker (actor)|George Baker]] for 13 episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sitcom.co.uk/sitcoms/bowler.shtml |title=British Comedy Guide - Bowler |website=Sitcom.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref>\n\nAs with many situation comedies of this era, a [[Please Sir! (film)|film version]] was released in 1971.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/movie/please-sir-v106243|title=Please Sir (1971) - Mark Stuart - Synopsis, Characteristics, Moods, Themes and Related - AllMovie|website=AllMovie}}</ref> This was set in an outdoor pursuit centre, but starred most of the TV cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6bfc62ad|title=Please Sir! (1972)|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n===Staff===\n*[[John Alderton]] as Mr Bernard Hedges (1968-1971)\n*[[Deryck Guyler]] as Mr Norman Potter\n*[[Noel Howlett]] as Mr Cromwell\n*[[Joan Sanderson]] as Miss Doris Ewell\n*[[Richard Davies (actor)|Richard Davies]] as Mr Price\n*[[Erik Chitty]] as Mr Smith\n*[[Bernard Holley]] as Mr Hurst (1971-1972)\n*Vivienne Martin as Miss Petting (1971-1972)\n*[[Richard Warwick]] as Mr David Ffitchett-Brown (1971)\n*David Howe as Colin Lovelace (1970-1971)\n*Lindsay Campbell as Mr Sibley (1970-1972)\n*[[Arnold Peters (actor)|Arnold Peters]] as School Governor (1970-1972)\n*Roderick Smith as Philip Larch (1971)\n\n===Pupils===\n====(1968\u201371)====\n*[[Liz Gebhardt]] as Maureen Bullock\n*[[Peter Cleall]] as Eric Duffy\n*[[David Barry (actor)|David Barry]] as Frankie Abbott\n*[[Peter Denyer]] as Dennis Dunstable\n*[[Penny Spencer]] as Sharon Eversleigh (1968-1970)\n*[[Carol Hawkins]] as Sharon Eversleigh (1971)\n*[[Malcolm McFee]] as Peter Craven (1968-1970)\n*[[Leon Vitali]] as Peter Craven (1971)\n\n====1971\u201372====\n*Charles Bolton as Godber\n*Rosemary Faith as Daisy\n*Billy Hamon as Des\n*Barry McCarthy as Terry Stringer\n*Drina Pavlovic as Celia\n*[[Shirley Cheriton]] as Pat (1971)\n\n==Episodes==\nNOTE: All of these episode descriptions have been taken from the DVD sleeves of the Please Sir DVDs, released by [[Network DVD|Network]] (In Australia, Series One and Two are available as one set of DVDs, Series Three (along with the 1971 ''Please Sir'' movie) as another).\n\nNote: The first series was in an experimental 40-minute format (to fit in a 45-minute slot). Repeats of some first series episodes were later edited down into the standard 25-minute (half hour) runtime, losing a considerable amount of footage (and on occasion, plot detail) as a result. The remaining episodes were in the traditional 25-minute format (to fit in a 30-minute slot)\n\nThe transmission dates and times reflect the listings for the London ITV region. Listings for the alternative ITV regions are not indicated.\n\n===Series One===\nThis series was recorded and transmitted in black and white on the [[VHF]] [[405-line]] TV system.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20px;\"| # !! Episode!! style=\"width:200px;\"|Writer/s !! Director !! Original ITV Airdate\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |Title=The Welcome Mat\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Friday {{Start date|1968|11|8|df=y}} 8:30pm\n |ShortSummary=When newly-qualified teacher Bernard Hedges arrives at Fenn Street [[Secondary Modern]] School to start his first job, even he hasn't bargained on what awaits him.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=2\n |Title=A Picture of Innocence\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Friday {{Start date|1968|11|15|df=y}} 8:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Bernard Hedges has to use all his tact when a member of the art club produces some stunning life studies of one of his unruly class - in the nude.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=3\n |Title=Maureen Bullock Loves Sir\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Friday {{Start date|1968|11|22|df=y}} 8:30pm\n |ShortSummary= Things start hotting up for Bernard Hedges when a pupil gets a crush on him. He thinks that he is settling into the district rather well, but when Maureen Bullock is seen leaving his new flat (after his class have helped him move into the flat), the rumours begin to fly.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=4\n |Title=A Near Greek Tragedy\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Friday {{Start date|1968|11|29|df=y}} 9:15pm\n |ShortSummary=This episode was shown later than usual as it contains swearing.\n\nApollon Abapellogopholis means more problems for Bernard Hedges. Pronouncing his name is trouble enough, but when Appollon rings the school fire alarm he decides to take firm measures with the boy.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=5\n |Title=Barbarian Librarians\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Friday {{Start date|1968|12|6|df=y}} 9:15pm\n |ShortSummary=This episode was shown later than usual as it contains swearing.\n\nBernard Hedges' touching faith in the virtues of 5C is often misplaced. The worst seems to have happened when he entrusts them with the library key in order to look after the library, outside school hours.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=6\n |Title=Student Princess\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Friday {{Start date|1968|12|13|df=y}} 8:30pm\n |ShortSummary=An old flame from Bernard's student days turns up as a trainee teacher. She disrupts not only his life but 5C's as well.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=7\n |Title=It's the Thought that Counts\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate= Friday {{Start date|1968|12|20|df=y}} 8:30pm\n |ShortSummary=End-of-term at Fenn Street, and the staff wait for their traditional presents from their forms. Bernard's anticipation at the thought of what he might get from 5C is tempered by the news that the injured Mr Wiggins will be fit to return as 5C's form master next term.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n|}\n\n===Series Two===\nAll of these episodes were made in colour, although all the episodes up to ''The Generation Gap'' were transmitted in [[monochrome]], as ITV began colour transmission on Saturday 15 November 1969. All were shown in colour in a repeat run, seen in some ITV regions in early 1970.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20px;\"| # !! Episode!! style=\"width:200px;\"|Writer/s !! Director !! Original ITV Airdate\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |Title=They're Off\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|9|20|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Bernard's attempts to teach maths by using betting as an example earns him admiration from not only 5C but a man who just happens to be painting the classroom walls.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=2\n |Title=Common Law\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|9|27|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=\nIt's 5C to the rescue when Sharon is attacked on the common going home. Suspicion falls on Potter the Caretaker but how can he prove his innocence?\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=3\n |Title=Panalal Passes By\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|10|4|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=\nBernard's efforts to stimulate interest in the Parent-teacher Association ends in chaos when Panalal, a young Indian boy, joins 5C.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=4\n |Title=The Sporting Life\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|10|11|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Bernard's new job as sports master gives him the chance to help Eric Duffy solve a problem. Then Eric decides that one good turn deserves another.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=5\n |Title=Norman's Conquest\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|10|18|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=\nPotter the caretaker fought in the North Africa regiment during [[World War II]] - known as the \"desert rats\". So when Form 5C get the chance to adopt an animal, they decide on a [[Jerboa]], otherwise known as a desert rat and decide to call him Norman.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=6\n |Title=X Certificate\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|10|25|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Fenn Street is having an open day and each class must contribute, even 5C. The only problem is that no-one told Bernard.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=7\n |Title=The Decent Thing\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|11|1|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=After a particularly raucous night out, Bernard wakes up in a strange bed in a state of alcoholic confusion. Things get worse when he discovers the bed belongs to Sharon's mother.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=8\n |Title=The Generation Gap\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|11|8|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Potter's on the warpath as someone has painted his wellies but 5C claim innocence. Bernard tries to get them interested in caring for [[geriatrics]] but the enthusiasm is lacking.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=9\n |Title=Life Without Doris\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|11|15|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Miss Ewell entertains an offer of migrating to Australia and the staff and kids rejoice. But if she goes then her role as Deputy Headteacher needs filling and Mr Price (science teacher) has his eye on it.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=10\n |Title=The School Captain\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|11|22|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=The Headmaster, Mr Cromwell, decides to divide the school into houses. But Bernard discovers that 5C's voting methods do not run along the normal lines.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=11\n |Title=Out of the Frying Pan\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|11|29|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Fenn Street School dinners are not very appetising, and teachers and pupils alike are avoiding them. Bernard does his best to remedy the situation, but he discovers Mr Potter is in league with the cook. Only the Headmaster considers the dinners to be tasty, but he doesn't realise that it isn't the school cook cooking them.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=12\n |Title=Mixed Doubles\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|12|6|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=The Headmaster invites the staff out to dinner to celebrate his birthday - at their own expense. Abbott endeavours to copy Duffy's technique with the opposite sex, but after a night out with Maureen Bullock, he only lands himself in trouble with the police.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=13\n |Title=Dress Circle\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|12|13|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=The staff arrange an outing to the theatre for the fifth form. But the redoubtable Miss Ewell dampens the enthusiasm of all concerned by disapproving of the choice of dress of some of the pupils. Annoyed at being sent home to change, Bernard and 5C plan - and get - their revenge later in the day.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n|}\n\n===Series Three===\nThe final three episodes of this series were affected by the [[Colour Strike|ITV Colour Strike]], which affected all ITV programmes recorded between November 1970 and March 1971. As a result of this industrial action, these affected episodes were recorded and transmitted in black and white.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! # !! Episode!! Writer/s !! Director !! Original ITV Airdate\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |Title=Ag Bow Rumber\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|9|20|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=\nA new term starts at Fenn Street and this means even more trouble for Bernard Hedges. Apart from the day-to-day hazards of teaching 5C, he has to prepare his unruly bunch for their imminent launching on an unsuspecting world. As prospective school leavers, 5C have to consider their future prospects. Bernard is also considering his, in the shapely form of Penny Wheeler (whom he met in the ''[[Please Sir! (film)|Please Sir!]]'' (1971) feature film, in which he took 5C on a two-week school trip to the Woodbridge Activity Centre). \n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=2\n |Title=Stitches and Hitches\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart.\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|9|27|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=\nBernard gets engaged - and Abbott gets [[appendicitis]].\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=3\n |Title=Knick Knack Taffy Whack\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|10|4|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=Why does one set about weighing Fenn Street School? It seems that Bernard believes that acts like this will help prepare 5C for their entry into the great, wide world at the end of this term.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=4\n |Title=Enter Mister Sibley\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|10|11|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=Duffy enters the embraces of the cold and harsh world outside school and finds it - cold and harsh.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=5\n |Title=It's a Saint Bernard's Life\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|10|18|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=When Smithy (Mr Smith) falls ill in the country, Bernard sees Reigate in all its rustic glory. He is quite smitten and dreams of the idyllic married life there, but his fiance, Penny, dreams otherwise.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=6\n |Title=Two and Two Make Nun\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|10|25|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=Maureen feels rejected - not only by Sir, but now by [[Monsignor]] Sopwith.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=7\n |Title=The Honour of the School\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|11|1|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=Bernard has an annoying habit of being honourable - even when playing golf. But what of his pupils? When Duffy invites Sharon to a half-term Majorcan holiday, will the habit be catching?\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=8\n |Title=Cromwell's Last Stand\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Alan Wallis\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|11|8|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=\nWhen \"Hank\" Abbott, private detective, goes into action, he opens the cupboards the lets out the skeletons. One produces a rash of honesty from Potter. The other makes Cromwell feel that Miss Ewell might yet be won back from Mr Sibley (careers advisor).\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=9\n |Title=Catch a Falling Drop-Out\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|11|15|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=Bernard and 5C drop in at the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Club]] and make new friends. Maureen also makes a new friend, but he is more interested in dropping out.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=10\n |Title=A Star is Born\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Alan Wallis\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|11|22|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=It takes a face in a thousand to star in an advertising campaign, but Bernard and Potter make it a two-horse race.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=11\n |Title=The Facts of Life\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Alan Wallis\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|11|29|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=\nWhen Bernard hears Abbott's version of the facts of life - which can only be described as high fiction - he feels that it is time to teach 5C the facts of life in an adult way. The only problem is, the Headmaster thinks that the rabbit reproductive system is good enough.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=12\n |Title=Situations Vacant\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Alan Wallis\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|12|6|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=With the end of the school term approaching, most of Fenn Street's form 5C are already fixed up with jobs, but animal-loving Dennis Dunstable still has no apparent future. Then Bernard has a brainwave which looks like the solution - he suggests Dennis for a stable-lad's job down at the local brewery. But Dennis's bullying, alcoholic dad won't let him work there due to a dispute with the pub's landlord.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=13\n |Title=Peace in Our Time\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|12|13|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=As 5C break up for the very last time, they prepare to take life by the throat, the shirt, the vest or anything else they can lay their hands on.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=14\n |Title=Christmas Special: And Everyone Came Too\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|12|27|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=Bernard and Penny dream of their wedding day: it should be the happiest day of their lives. However, Potter is chief usher, class 5C are guests, the meteorological department forecasts snow and there are those inevitable unforeseen problems. So their dream acquires all the elements of a nightmare.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n|}\n\n===Series Four===\nUnlike the previous series, episodes were initially broadcast on a Saturday. However, there was a week's break in transmission between Episode 14 (''Old Fennians Day'') and Episode 15 (''What Are You Incinerating''). When it returned it was broadcast in a Sunday night slot. This was only in London. In the other ITV regions, it continued to be broadcast on Saturdays at 6:30pm, so the rest of the nation saw the last 7 episodes of this series one day before Londoners saw them.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20px;\"| # !! Episode!! style=\"width:200px;\"|Writer/s !! Director !! Original ITV Airdate\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |Title=Identitwit\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Philip Casson\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|9|18|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Bernard has to say goodbye to his 5C class at Fenn Street School but his new class (4C) brings some unexpected problems.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=2\n |Title=The Pruning of Hedges\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|9|25|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Bernard has finally decided to leave Fenn Street School, but he finds that resigning is not as simple as he had imagined.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=3\n |Title=Vive La Revolution\n |Aux1=Geoff Rowley and Andy Baker\n |Aux2=Philip Casson\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|10|2|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=All contributions are gratefully accepted when magazine time comes around at Fenn Street School. But headmaster Cromwell's efforts to muster his usual support are thwarted by an irate local shopkeeper and Fenn Street's alternative press - The Fenntasy.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=4\n |Title=A Rather Nasty Outbreak\n |Aux1=[[Tony Bilbow]]\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|10|9|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Guest: [[Peter Cleall]]\n\nGeorgie Duffy is nervous. He is due to start his first term at Fenn Street School - three weeks late. But big brother Eric, a member of last year's 5C and an old hand at dealing with authority, explains that there is nothing to worry about. No-one, however, has taken into account the arrival of new master Gregory Dix on the scene.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=5\n |Title=David and Goliath\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Philip Casson\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|10|16|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Bernard Hedges has left Fenn Street School and the gap has been filled by Mr Dix, a living example of everything a teacher should not be. The staff long for a new young champion to challenge this tyrant, but when David Ffitchett-Brown arrives wearing beads, they wonder just what sort of champion they have.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=6\n |Title=[[Absent Without Official Leave|AWOL]]\n |Aux1=Geoff Rowley and Andy Baker\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|10|23|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Cromwell's [[yo-yo]] obsession helps distract him from David's request for new school supplies, including a new [[television set]] that Mr Price attacked with [[Nitric Acid]] after his horse had lost a horse race. But between themselves and Potter they work out a cunning plan.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=7\n |Title=What's a Class Between Friends?\n |Aux1=Geoff Rowley and Andy Baker\n |Aux2=Philip Casson\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|10|30|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Guest: [[Mollie Sugden]]\n\nWhen Cromwell succumbs to an attack of administrative megalomania, the [[Charge of the Light Brigade]] is cancelled, a class is lost at the cinema and Mr Price is driven to drink.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=8\n |Title=Our Mr Price\n |Aux1=Tony Bilbow\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|11|6|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=It looks as though Fenn Street will lose yet another teacher when Price applies for a job in industry. But can he really make the break?\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=9\n |Title=Black Power\n |Aux1=Tony Bilbow\n |Aux2=Philip Casson\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|11|13|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Guest: [[Derek Griffiths]]\n\nPotter's repeated demands for an assistant are finally heeded, and Sidney Noakes arrives at Fenn Street.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=10\n |Title=False Alarm\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|11|20|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=\nThe amalgamation with neighbouring Weaver Street and the possibility of Fenn Street going comprehensive is more than the Fenn Street staff can cope with. And even Potter has to decide where his loyalties lie.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=11\n |Title=Sibley, Mumsie, Dodo and Georgie\n |Aux1=Geoff Rowley and Andy Baker\n |Aux2=Philip Casson\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|11|27|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=For Miss Ewell, life is not exactly a bowl of cherries at the moment. There is the school inspection to be organised, and the new Weaver Street kids to keep under control. But then, Doris can always turn to Mr Sibley for comfort - at least until mother's interferences.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=12\n |Title=United we Sit\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|12|4|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Headmaster Cromwell makes a new rule about haircuts and skirts at Fenn Street School. But the kids won't take this lying down - they decide on a sit-in to ask for pupil representation on staff meetings.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=13\n |Title=Nemesis for Norman\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Philip Casson\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|12|11|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=\nPotter's boasting about his war career gets out of hand when he is chosen to carry the banner at his [[El Alamein]] reunion.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=14\n |Title=Old Fennians Day\n |Aux1=Tony Bilbow\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|12|18|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=\nCromwell's latest idea is a school song for the first meeting of his newly-formed Old Fennians Association. With the staff bursting into a flurry of musical activity, and the return of the old Form 5C for the big event, it is a day to remember.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=15\n |Title=What Are You Incinerating\n |Aux1=Geoff Rowley and Andy Baker\n |Aux2=Philip Casson\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1972|1|2|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=The headmaster's \"Clean Up Fenn Street\" campaign is in full swing. But when Potter takes on some temporary assistance, an explosive situation develops which threatens to clean up Fenn Street for good.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=16\n |Title=The Ugly Ducklings\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1972|1|9|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=\nMiss Ewell gets her \"[[Royal Canadian Mounted Police|mountie]]\", Miss Petting her mandarin and Daisy her \"prince\".\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=17\n |Title=Cup Fever\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Philip Casson\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1972|1|16|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=Fenn Street School makes sporting history when its football team reaches the semi-final of the district cup. But Miss Ewell has a match of her own with the star of the team, and if she wins, the school loses.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=18\n |Title=Please Give Generously\n |Aux1=Geoff Rowley and Andy Baker\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1972|1|23|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=\nWhen Fenn Street School holds a charity walk for the local \"old and needy\", the staff are confident of its success. But deciding just who the \"needy\" are can be a tricky business.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=19\n |Title=Blodwyn All Over\n |Aux1=Geoff Rowley and Andy Baker\n |Aux2=Alan Wallis\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1972|1|30|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=When the chairman of the Fenn Street School governors makes rash promises to his \"niece\", the whole school is affected. Cromwell gets a secretary, the kids get a pin-up, and Pricey gets a whole new outlook on life.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=20\n |Title=The Price War\n |Aux1=Tony Bilbow\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1972|2|6|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=Headmaster Cromwell has a new toy to help him communicate with the whole school, but Price does not want to keep in touch, for an old enemy is out to get him.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=21\n |Title=The Fixer\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1972|2|13|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=Wedding bells ring out for Miss Ewell and Mr Sibley. Meanwhile, Potter's ding-dong with his wife Ruby ends in a fly-away flourish.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n|}\n\n==Characters==\n\n<big>'''Staff'''</big>\n\n'''Mr Bernard Hedges''' (Portrayed by [[John Alderton]]). A teacher fresh out of training. He was allocated Class 5C, the most unruly form in the \nschool, at the beginning of term. At first relations were frosty between Bernard and Class 5C, but gradually Bernard gained the respect \nof his class and the rest of the staff. As the series progressed, he is shown to be a caring and very fair teacher and would always defend \nhis form, regardless of how much evidence is put towards them.\n\nIn the movie, he met air stewardess Penny Wheeler. After misinterpreting a 'few white lies' made by a pupil accidentally left behind, Penny   \nbegan to take shine to Bernard. After a period of dating, Bernard attempted to propose to Penny but she already said yes before he could complete his sentence and they got engaged and later married.\n\nShortly after Bernard got married, a new term started and was allocated Class 4C but it was not quite the same as 5C. He later resigned and left.\n\n'''Mr Norman Potter''' (Portrayed by [[Deryck Guyler]]). The pedantic and officious school caretaker. He claimed to have been a Desert Rat and constantly complains about the unruly behaviour of Hedge's class 5C. He is fiercely loyal (to the point of sycophancy) to the headmaster but a thorn in the side of the rest of the staff. His various comeuppances provide much of the ongoing humour of the sitcom.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of films based on British sitcoms]]\n* [[Welcome Back, Kotter]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{British Comedy Guide|tv|please_sir|Please Sir!'' (TV series)}}\n*{{IMDb title|id=0063941|title=Please Sir!'' (TV series)}}\n*{{IMDb title|id=0067591|title=Please Sir!'' (film)}}\n\n{{Esmonde Larbey}}\n\n[[Category:1960s British sitcoms]]\n[[Category:1960s British workplace comedy television series]]\n[[Category:1970s British sitcoms]]\n[[Category:1970s British workplace comedy television series]]\n[[Category:1968 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1972 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:ITV sitcoms]]\n[[Category:Television series by ITV Studios]]\n[[Category:London Weekend Television programmes]]\n[[Category:British high school television series]]\n[[Category:Television programs adapted into films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2014}}\n{{Refimprove|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox television\n | image = Please_Sir!_(TV_series).jpg\n | caption = Opening title card\n | show_name = Please Sir!\n | runtime = 25-45 minutes\n | creator =  \n | starring = [[John Alderton]]<br />[[Deryck Guyler]]<br />[[Noel Howlett]]<br />[[Joan Sanderson]]<br />[[Richard Davies (actor)|Richard Davies]]<br />[[Erik Chitty]]<br />[[David Barry (actor)|David Barry]]<br />[[Peter Cleall]]<br />[[Peter Denyer]]<br />[[Liz Gebhardt]]<br />[[Malcolm McFee]]<br />[[Penny Spencer]]<br />[[Carol Hawkins]]<br />[[Richard Warwick]] \n | country = United Kingdom\n | language = English\n | picture_format = [[4:3]]\n | audio_format = [[Monaural|Mono]]\n| theme_music_composer     = [[Sam Fonteyn]]\n| opentheme                = \"School's Out\"\n| endtheme                 = \n | company = [[London Weekend Television]]\n | distributor = [[ITV Studios]]\n | network = [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n | first_aired = {{Start date|1968|11|8|df=y}}\n | last_aired = {{End date|1972|2|12|df=y}}\n | num_series  = 4\n | num_episodes = 55\n | related = ''[[The Fenn Street Gang]]''\n}}\n'''''Please Sir!''''' is a [[London Weekend Television]] [[situation comedy]] for [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]], created by [[Esmonde and Larbey|John Esmonde]] and [[Esmonde and Larbey|Bob Larbey]] and featuring actors [[John Alderton]], [[Deryck Guyler]], [[Penny Spencer]], [[Joan Sanderson]], [[Noel Howlett]], [[Erik Chitty]] and [[Richard Davies (actor)|Richard Davies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.televisionheaven.co.uk/pleasesir.htm |title=Please Sir! &#124; A Television Heaven Review |website=Televisionheaven.co.uk |date=1972-02-13 |accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref> The series ran for 55 episodes between 1968 and 1972.<ref name=comedy>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.sitcom.co.uk/please_sir/index.shtml |title=Please Sir! - ITV Sitcom - British Comedy Guide |website=Sitcom.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref>\n\nThe theme tune \"School's Out\" was by [[Sam Fonteyn]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=44ElLnnG_Tg|title=Top TV Soundtrack Themes. Please Sir|first=|last=bishdaboo|date=9 October 2011|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0067591/soundtrack|title=Please Sir! (1971)|publisher=www.imdb.com}|accessdate=8 January 2018}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nThe programme was set in the fictional Fenn Street Secondary Modern School, and starred John Alderton as Bernard Hedges, a young teacher fresh out of training college.<ref name=comedy/> The supporting cast included Deryck Guyler, Joan Sanderson and Richard Davies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nostalgiacentral.com/television/tv-by-decade/tv-shows-1960s/please-sir/|title=Please, Sir! - Nostalgia Central|website=nostalgiacentral.com}}</ref> Character actors and actresses formed the guest cast, including [[Mollie Sugden]] as a parent of one of the pupils, [[Barbara Mitchell]] as Frankie Abbott's mother, and [[Ann Lancaster]] as Mrs Pearce in a pair of 1968 episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b847eecda|title=What&#039;s a Class between Friends (1971)|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/please_sir/episodes/2/3/|title=Please Sir! Series 2, Episode 3 - Panalal Passes By - British Comedy Guide|first=British Comedy|last=Guide|website=British Comedy Guide}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b84787f82|title=A Near Greek Tragedy (1968)|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6b2efc81|title=Maureen Bullock Loves Sir (1968)|publisher=}}</ref>.\n\nBernard Hedges and the 5C pupils were replaced by a new teacher and pupils for the final series in 1971\u201372, while the original pupils continued in a spin-off series, ''[[The Fenn Street Gang]]'', which ran for 47 episodes between 1971 and 1972.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sitcom.co.uk/fenn_street/ |title=British Comedy Guide - The Fenn Street Gang |website=Sitcom.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref> This was followed by ''[[Bowler (TV series)|Bowler]]'' (1973), following crime boss Stanley Bowler, played by [[George Baker (actor)|George Baker]] for 13 episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sitcom.co.uk/sitcoms/bowler.shtml |title=British Comedy Guide - Bowler |website=Sitcom.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref>\n\nAs with many situation comedies of this era, a [[Please Sir! (film)|film version]] was released in 1971.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/movie/please-sir-v106243|title=Please Sir (1971) - Mark Stuart - Synopsis, Characteristics, Moods, Themes and Related - AllMovie|website=AllMovie}}</ref> This was set in an outdoor pursuit centre, but starred most of the TV cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6bfc62ad|title=Please Sir! (1972)|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n===Staff===\n*[[John Alderton]] as Mr Bernard Hedges (1968-1971)\n*[[Deryck Guyler]] as Mr Norman Potter\n*[[Noel Howlett]] as Mr Cromwell\n*[[Joan Sanderson]] as Miss Doris Ewell\n*[[Richard Davies (actor)|Richard Davies]] as Mr Price\n*[[Erik Chitty]] as Mr Smith\n*[[Bernard Holley]] as Mr Hurst (1971-1972)\n*Vivienne Martin as Miss Petting (1971-1972)\n*[[Richard Warwick]] as Mr David Ffitchett-Brown (1971)\n*David Howe as Colin Lovelace (1970-1971)\n*Lindsay Campbell as Mr Sibley (1970-1972)\n*[[Arnold Peters (actor)|Arnold Peters]] as School Governor (1970-1972)\n*Roderick Smith as Philip Larch (1971)\n\n===Pupils===\n====(1968\u201371)====\n*[[Liz Gebhardt]] as Maureen Bullock\n*[[Peter Cleall]] as Eric Duffy\n*[[David Barry (actor)|David Barry]] as Frankie Abbott\n*[[Peter Denyer]] as Dennis Dunstable\n*[[Penny Spencer]] as Sharon Eversleigh (1968-1970)\n*[[Carol Hawkins]] as Sharon Eversleigh (1971)\n*[[Malcolm McFee]] as Peter Craven (1968-1970)\n*[[Leon Vitali]] as Peter Craven (1971)\n\n====1971\u201372====\n*Charles Bolton as Godber\n*Rosemary Faith as Daisy\n*Billy Hamon as Des\n*Barry McCarthy as Terry Stringer\n*Drina Pavlovic as Celia\n*[[Shirley Cheriton]] as Pat (1971)\n\n==Episodes==\nNOTE: All of these episode descriptions have been taken from the DVD sleeves of the Please Sir DVDs, released by [[Network DVD|Network]] (In Australia, Series One and Two are available as one set of DVDs, Series Three (along with the 1971 ''Please Sir'' movie) as another).\n\nNote: The first series was in an experimental 40-minute format (to fit in a 45-minute slot). Repeats of some first series episodes were later edited down into the standard 25-minute (half hour) runtime, losing a considerable amount of footage (and on occasion, plot detail) as a result. The remaining episodes were in the traditional 25-minute format (to fit in a 30-minute slot)\n\nThe transmission dates and times reflect the listings for the London ITV region. Listings for the alternative ITV regions are not indicated.\n\n===Series One===\nThis series was recorded and transmitted in black and white on the [[VHF]] [[405-line]] TV system.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20px;\"| # !! Episode!! style=\"width:200px;\"|Writer/s !! Director !! Original ITV Airdate\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |Title=The Welcome Mat\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Friday {{Start date|1968|11|8|df=y}} 8:30pm\n |ShortSummary=When newly-qualified teacher Bernard Hedges arrives at Fenn Street [[Secondary Modern]] School to start his first job, even he hasn't bargained on what awaits him.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=2\n |Title=A Picture of Innocence\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Friday {{Start date|1968|11|15|df=y}} 8:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Bernard Hedges has to use all his tact when a member of the art club produces some stunning life studies of one of his unruly class - in the nude.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=3\n |Title=Maureen Bullock Loves Sir\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Friday {{Start date|1968|11|22|df=y}} 8:30pm\n |ShortSummary= Things start hotting up for Bernard Hedges when a pupil gets a crush on him. He thinks that he is settling into the district rather well, but when Maureen Bullock is seen leaving his new flat (after his class have helped him move into the flat), the rumours begin to fly.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=4\n |Title=A Near Greek Tragedy\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Friday {{Start date|1968|11|29|df=y}} 9:15pm\n |ShortSummary=This episode was shown later than usual as it contains swearing.\n\nApollon Abapellogopholis means more problems for Bernard Hedges. Pronouncing his name is trouble enough, but when Appollon rings the school fire alarm he decides to take firm measures with the boy.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=5\n |Title=Barbarian Librarians\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Friday {{Start date|1968|12|6|df=y}} 9:15pm\n |ShortSummary=This episode was shown later than usual as it contains swearing.\n\nBernard Hedges' touching faith in the virtues of 5C is often misplaced. The worst seems to have happened when he entrusts them with the library key in order to look after the library, outside school hours.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=6\n |Title=Student Princess\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Friday {{Start date|1968|12|13|df=y}} 8:30pm\n |ShortSummary=An old flame from Bernard's student days turns up as a trainee teacher. She disrupts not only his life but 5C's as well.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=7\n |Title=It's the Thought that Counts\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate= Friday {{Start date|1968|12|20|df=y}} 8:30pm\n |ShortSummary=End-of-term at Fenn Street, and the staff wait for their traditional presents from their forms. Bernard's anticipation at the thought of what he might get from 5C is tempered by the news that the injured Mr Wiggins will be fit to return as 5C's form master next term.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n|}\n\n===Series Two===\nAll of these episodes were made in colour, although all the episodes up to ''The Generation Gap'' were transmitted in [[monochrome]], as ITV began colour transmission on Saturday 15 November 1969. All were shown in colour in a repeat run, seen in some ITV regions in early 1970.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20px;\"| # !! Episode!! style=\"width:200px;\"|Writer/s !! Director !! Original ITV Airdate\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |Title=They're Off\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|9|20|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Bernard's attempts to teach maths by using betting as an example earns him admiration from not only 5C but a man who just happens to be painting the classroom walls.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=2\n |Title=Common Law\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|9|27|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=\nIt's 5C to the rescue when Sharon is attacked on the common going home. Suspicion falls on Potter the Caretaker but how can he prove his innocence?\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=3\n |Title=Panalal Passes By\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|10|4|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=\nBernard's efforts to stimulate interest in the Parent-teacher Association ends in chaos when Panalal, a young Indian boy, joins 5C.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=4\n |Title=The Sporting Life\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|10|11|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Bernard's new job as sports master gives him the chance to help Eric Duffy solve a problem. Then Eric decides that one good turn deserves another.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=5\n |Title=Norman's Conquest\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|10|18|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=\nPotter the caretaker fought in the North Africa regiment during [[World War II]] - known as the \"desert rats\". So when Form 5C get the chance to adopt an animal, they decide on a [[Jerboa]], otherwise known as a desert rat and decide to call him Norman.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=6\n |Title=X Certificate\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|10|25|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Fenn Street is having an open day and each class must contribute, even 5C. The only problem is that no-one told Bernard.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=7\n |Title=The Decent Thing\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|11|1|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=After a particularly raucous night out, Bernard wakes up in a strange bed in a state of alcoholic confusion. Things get worse when he discovers the bed belongs to Sharon's mother.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=8\n |Title=The Generation Gap\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|11|8|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Potter's on the warpath as someone has painted his wellies but 5C claim innocence. Bernard tries to get them interested in caring for [[geriatrics]] but the enthusiasm is lacking.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=9\n |Title=Life Without Doris\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|11|15|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Miss Ewell entertains an offer of migrating to Australia and the staff and kids rejoice. But if she goes then her role as Deputy Headteacher needs filling and Mr Price (science teacher) has his eye on it.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=10\n |Title=The School Captain\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|11|22|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=The Headmaster, Mr Cromwell, decides to divide the school into houses. But Bernard discovers that 5C's voting methods do not run along the normal lines.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=11\n |Title=Out of the Frying Pan\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|11|29|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Fenn Street School dinners are not very appetising, and teachers and pupils alike are avoiding them. Bernard does his best to remedy the situation, but he discovers Mr Potter is in league with the cook. Only the Headmaster considers the dinners to be tasty, but he doesn't realise that it isn't the school cook cooking them.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=12\n |Title=Mixed Doubles\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|12|6|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=The Headmaster invites the staff out to dinner to celebrate his birthday - at their own expense. Abbott endeavours to copy Duffy's technique with the opposite sex, but after a night out with Maureen Bullock, he only lands himself in trouble with the police.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=13\n |Title=Dress Circle\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1969|12|13|df=y}} 7:30pm\n |ShortSummary=The staff arrange an outing to the theatre for the fifth form. But the redoubtable Miss Ewell dampens the enthusiasm of all concerned by disapproving of the choice of dress of some of the pupils. Annoyed at being sent home to change, Bernard and 5C plan - and get - their revenge later in the day.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n|}\n\n===Series Three===\nThe final three episodes of this series were affected by the [[Colour Strike|ITV Colour Strike]], which affected all ITV programmes recorded between November 1970 and March 1971. As a result of this industrial action, these affected episodes were recorded and transmitted in black and white.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! # !! Episode!! Writer/s !! Director !! Original ITV Airdate\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |Title=Ag Bow Rumber\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|9|20|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=\nA new term starts at Fenn Street and this means even more trouble for Bernard Hedges. Apart from the day-to-day hazards of teaching 5C, he has to prepare his unruly bunch for their imminent launching on an unsuspecting world. As prospective school leavers, 5C have to consider their future prospects. Bernard is also considering his, in the shapely form of Penny Wheeler (whom he met in the ''[[Please Sir! (film)|Please Sir!]]'' (1971) feature film, in which he took 5C on a two-week school trip to the Woodbridge Activity Centre). \n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=2\n |Title=Stitches and Hitches\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart.\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|9|27|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=\nBernard gets engaged - and Abbott gets [[appendicitis]].\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=3\n |Title=Knick Knack Taffy Whack\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|10|4|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=Why does one set about weighing Fenn Street School? It seems that Bernard believes that acts like this will help prepare 5C for their entry into the great, wide world at the end of this term.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=4\n |Title=Enter Mister Sibley\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|10|11|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=Duffy enters the embraces of the cold and harsh world outside school and finds it - cold and harsh.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=5\n |Title=It's a Saint Bernard's Life\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|10|18|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=When Smithy (Mr Smith) falls ill in the country, Bernard sees Reigate in all its rustic glory. He is quite smitten and dreams of the idyllic married life there, but his fiance, Penny, dreams otherwise.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=6\n |Title=Two and Two Make Nun\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|10|25|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=Maureen feels rejected - not only by Sir, but now by [[Monsignor]] Sopwith.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=7\n |Title=The Honour of the School\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|11|1|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=Bernard has an annoying habit of being honourable - even when playing golf. But what of his pupils? When Duffy invites Sharon to a half-term Majorcan holiday, will the habit be catching?\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=8\n |Title=Cromwell's Last Stand\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Alan Wallis\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|11|8|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=\nWhen \"Hank\" Abbott, private detective, goes into action, he opens the cupboards the lets out the skeletons. One produces a rash of honesty from Potter. The other makes Cromwell feel that Miss Ewell might yet be won back from Mr Sibley (careers advisor).\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=9\n |Title=Catch a Falling Drop-Out\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|11|15|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=Bernard and 5C drop in at the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Club]] and make new friends. Maureen also makes a new friend, but he is more interested in dropping out.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=10\n |Title=A Star is Born\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Alan Wallis\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|11|22|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=It takes a face in a thousand to star in an advertising campaign, but Bernard and Potter make it a two-horse race.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=11\n |Title=The Facts of Life\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Alan Wallis\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|11|29|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=\nWhen Bernard hears Abbott's version of the facts of life - which can only be described as high fiction - he feels that it is time to teach 5C the facts of life in an adult way. The only problem is, the Headmaster thinks that the rabbit reproductive system is good enough.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=12\n |Title=Situations Vacant\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Alan Wallis\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|12|6|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=With the end of the school term approaching, most of Fenn Street's form 5C are already fixed up with jobs, but animal-loving Dennis Dunstable still has no apparent future. Then Bernard has a brainwave which looks like the solution - he suggests Dennis for a stable-lad's job down at the local brewery. But Dennis's bullying, alcoholic dad won't let him work there due to a dispute with the pub's landlord.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=13\n |Title=Peace in Our Time\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|12|13|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=As 5C break up for the very last time, they prepare to take life by the throat, the shirt, the vest or anything else they can lay their hands on.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=14\n |Title=Christmas Special: And Everyone Came Too\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Mark Stuart\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1970|12|27|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=Bernard and Penny dream of their wedding day: it should be the happiest day of their lives. However, Potter is chief usher, class 5C are guests, the meteorological department forecasts snow and there are those inevitable unforeseen problems. So their dream acquires all the elements of a nightmare.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n|}\n\n===Series Four===\nUnlike the previous series, episodes were initially broadcast on a Saturday. However, there was a week's break in transmission between Episode 14 (''Old Fennians Day'') and Episode 15 (''What Are You Incinerating''). When it returned it was broadcast in a Sunday night slot. This was only in London. In the other ITV regions, it continued to be broadcast on Saturdays at 6:30pm, so the rest of the nation saw the last 7 episodes of this series one day before Londoners saw them.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20px;\"| # !! Episode!! style=\"width:200px;\"|Writer/s !! Director !! Original ITV Airdate\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |Title=Identitwit\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Philip Casson\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|9|18|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Bernard has to say goodbye to his 5C class at Fenn Street School but his new class (4C) brings some unexpected problems.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=2\n |Title=The Pruning of Hedges\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|9|25|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Bernard has finally decided to leave Fenn Street School, but he finds that resigning is not as simple as he had imagined.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=3\n |Title=Vive La Revolution\n |Aux1=Geoff Rowley and Andy Baker\n |Aux2=Philip Casson\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|10|2|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=All contributions are gratefully accepted when magazine time comes around at Fenn Street School. But headmaster Cromwell's efforts to muster his usual support are thwarted by an irate local shopkeeper and Fenn Street's alternative press - The Fenntasy.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=4\n |Title=A Rather Nasty Outbreak\n |Aux1=[[Tony Bilbow]]\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|10|9|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Guest: [[Peter Cleall]]\n\nGeorgie Duffy is nervous. He is due to start his first term at Fenn Street School - three weeks late. But big brother Eric, a member of last year's 5C and an old hand at dealing with authority, explains that there is nothing to worry about. No-one, however, has taken into account the arrival of new master Gregory Dix on the scene.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=5\n |Title=David and Goliath\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Philip Casson\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|10|16|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Bernard Hedges has left Fenn Street School and the gap has been filled by Mr Dix, a living example of everything a teacher should be. The staff long for a new young champion to challenge this tyrant, but when David Ffitchett-Brown arrives wearing beads, they wonder just what sort of champion they have.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=6\n |Title=[[Absent Without Official Leave|AWOL]]\n |Aux1=Geoff Rowley and Andy Baker\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|10|23|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Cromwell's [[yo-yo]] obsession helps distract him from David's request for new school supplies, including a new [[television set]] that Mr Price attacked with [[Nitric Acid]] after his horse had lost a horse race. But between themselves and Potter they work out a cunning plan.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=7\n |Title=What's a Class Between Friends?\n |Aux1=Geoff Rowley and Andy Baker\n |Aux2=Philip Casson\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|10|30|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Guest: [[Mollie Sugden]]\n\nWhen Cromwell succumbs to an attack of administrative megalomania, the [[Charge of the Light Brigade]] is cancelled, a class is lost at the cinema and Mr Price is driven to drink.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=8\n |Title=Our Mr Price\n |Aux1=Tony Bilbow\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|11|6|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=It looks as though Fenn Street will lose yet another teacher when Price applies for a job in industry. But can he really make the break?\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=9\n |Title=Black Power\n |Aux1=Tony Bilbow\n |Aux2=Philip Casson\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|11|13|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Guest: [[Derek Griffiths]]\n\nPotter's repeated demands for an assistant are finally heeded, and Sidney Noakes arrives at Fenn Street.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=10\n |Title=False Alarm\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|11|20|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=\nThe amalgamation with neighbouring Weaver Street and the possibility of Fenn Street going comprehensive is more than the Fenn Street staff can cope with. And even Potter has to decide where his loyalties lie.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=11\n |Title=Sibley, Mumsie, Dodo and Georgie\n |Aux1=Geoff Rowley and Andy Baker\n |Aux2=Philip Casson\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|11|27|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=For Miss Ewell, life is not exactly a bowl of cherries at the moment. There is the school inspection to be organised, and the new Weaver Street kids to keep under control. But then, Doris can always turn to Mr Sibley for comfort - at least until mother's interferences.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=12\n |Title=United we Sit\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|12|4|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=Headmaster Cromwell makes a new rule about haircuts and skirts at Fenn Street School. But the kids won't take this lying down - they decide on a sit-in to ask for pupil representation on staff meetings.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=13\n |Title=Nemesis for Norman\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Philip Casson\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|12|11|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=\nPotter's boasting about his war career gets out of hand when he is chosen to carry the banner at his [[El Alamein]] reunion.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=14\n |Title=Old Fennians Day\n |Aux1=Tony Bilbow\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Saturday {{Start date|1971|12|18|df=y}} 6:30pm\n |ShortSummary=\nCromwell's latest idea is a school song for the first meeting of his newly-formed Old Fennians Association. With the staff bursting into a flurry of musical activity, and the return of the old Form 5C for the big event, it is a day to remember.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=15\n |Title=What Are You Incinerating\n |Aux1=Geoff Rowley and Andy Baker\n |Aux2=Philip Casson\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1972|1|2|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=The headmaster's \"Clean Up Fenn Street\" campaign is in full swing. But when Potter takes on some temporary assistance, an explosive situation develops which threatens to clean up Fenn Street for good.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=16\n |Title=The Ugly Ducklings\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1972|1|9|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=\nMiss Ewell gets her \"[[Royal Canadian Mounted Police|mountie]]\", Miss Petting her mandarin and Daisy her \"prince\".\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=17\n |Title=Cup Fever\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Philip Casson\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1972|1|16|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=Fenn Street School makes sporting history when its football team reaches the semi-final of the district cup. But Miss Ewell has a match of her own with the star of the team, and if she wins, the school loses.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=18\n |Title=Please Give Generously\n |Aux1=Geoff Rowley and Andy Baker\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1972|1|23|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=\nWhen Fenn Street School holds a charity walk for the local \"old and needy\", the staff are confident of its success. But deciding just who the \"needy\" are can be a tricky business.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=19\n |Title=Blodwyn All Over\n |Aux1=Geoff Rowley and Andy Baker\n |Aux2=Alan Wallis\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1972|1|30|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=When the chairman of the Fenn Street School governors makes rash promises to his \"niece\", the whole school is affected. Cromwell gets a secretary, the kids get a pin-up, and Pricey gets a whole new outlook on life.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=20\n |Title=The Price War\n |Aux1=Tony Bilbow\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1972|2|6|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=Headmaster Cromwell has a new toy to help him communicate with the whole school, but Price does not want to keep in touch, for an old enemy is out to get him.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=21\n |Title=The Fixer\n |Aux1=John Esmonde and Bob Larbey\n |Aux2=Howard Ross\n |OriginalAirDate=Sunday {{Start date|1972|2|13|df=y}} 7:25pm\n |ShortSummary=Wedding bells ring out for Miss Ewell and Mr Sibley. Meanwhile, Potter's ding-dong with his wife Ruby ends in a fly-away flourish.\n |LineColor=99CCFF\n}}\n|}\n\n==Characters==\n\n<big>'''Staff'''</big>\n\n'''Mr Bernard Hedges''' (Portrayed by [[John Alderton]]). A teacher fresh out of training. He was allocated Class 5C, the most unruly form in the \nschool, at the beginning of term. At first relations were frosty between Bernard and Class 5C, but gradually Bernard gained the respect \nof his class and the rest of the staff. As the series progressed, he is shown to be a caring and very fair teacher and would always defend \nhis form, regardless of how much evidence is put towards them.\n\nIn the movie, he met air stewardess Penny Wheeler. After misinterpreting a 'few white lies' made by a pupil accidentally left behind, Penny   \nbegan to take shine to Bernard. After a period of dating, Bernard attempted to propose to Penny but she already said yes before he could complete his sentence and they got engaged and later married.\n\nShortly after Bernard got married, a new term started and was allocated Class 4C but it was not quite the same as 5C. He later resigned and left.\n\n'''Mr Norman Potter''' (Portrayed by [[Deryck Guyler]]). The pedantic and officious school caretaker. He claimed to have been a Desert Rat and constantly complains about the unruly behaviour of Hedge's class 5C. He is fiercely loyal (to the point of sycophancy) to the headmaster but a thorn in the side of the rest of the staff. His various comeuppances provide much of the ongoing humour of the sitcom.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of films based on British sitcoms]]\n* [[Welcome Back, Kotter]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{British Comedy Guide|tv|please_sir|Please Sir!'' (TV series)}}\n*{{IMDb title|id=0063941|title=Please Sir!'' (TV series)}}\n*{{IMDb title|id=0067591|title=Please Sir!'' (film)}}\n\n{{Esmonde Larbey}}\n\n[[Category:1960s British sitcoms]]\n[[Category:1960s British workplace comedy television series]]\n[[Category:1970s British sitcoms]]\n[[Category:1970s British workplace comedy television series]]\n[[Category:1968 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1972 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:ITV sitcoms]]\n[[Category:Television series by ITV Studios]]\n[[Category:London Weekend Television programmes]]\n[[Category:British high school television series]]\n[[Category:Television programs adapted into films]]\n", "name_user": "PRL42", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEpisodes:Add missing word.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Please_Sir!"}
