ast of Taiwan) [[Taipei]]-[[Taichung]]-[[Kaohsiung]]||Taiwan||18,000,000\n|-\n|}\n\n==Largest metropolitan areas==\n{{Main|List of largest cities#Metropolitan area}}\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!Rank!!Metropolitan area!!Country!!Population!!Area (km\u00b2)!!Population Density (People/km\u00b2)\n|- \t \t\n|1||[[Greater Tokyo Area|Tokyo]]||Japan||32,450,000||8,014||4,049\n|-\n|2||[[Seoul Capital Region|Seoul]]||South Korea||20,550,000||5,076||4,048\n|-\n|3||[[Mumbai]] (Bombay)||India||20,900,000||8,100||2,580\n|-\n|4||[[Jabotabek|Jakarta]]||Indonesia||18,900,000||5,100||3,706\n|-\n|5||[[Shanghai]]||China||16,650,000||5,177||3,216\n|-\n|6||[[Hong Kong]]-[[Shenzhen]]<ref>There are restrictions on the movement of labor between Hong Kong and Mainland China and the two areas are usually listed separately in other lists.</ref>||China||15,800,000||3,051||5,179\n|-\n|7||[[Beijing]]||China||12,500,000||6,562||1,905\n|}\n\n==Largest urban areas ranked by 2010 projected population==\n{{Main|List of largest cities#Urban area}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Rank\n!City\n!Country\n!Population\n!Area (km\u00b2)\n!Density (km\u00b2)\n!Sources of\nPop. / Area\n!Image\n|-\n|1\n|[[Tokyo]]\u2013[[Yokohama]]<ref>Includes large portions of the prefectures of Tokyo, [[Kanagawa Prefecture|Kanagawa]], [[Chiba Prefecture|Chiba]] and [[Saitama Prefecture|Saitama]]; and small portions of [[Gunma Prefecture|Gunma]], [[Tochigi Prefecture|Tochigi]] and [[Ibaraki Prefecture|Ibaraki]]. Excludes urban areas of [[Utsunomiya, Tochigi|Utsunomiya]] (500,000; 88 km\u00b2) and [[Mito, Ibaraki|Mito]] (500,000; 246 km\u00b2).</ref>\n|Japan\n|35,200,000\n|7,835\n|4,100\n|C / B\n|[[File:Tokyo Skytree View Night 450m.jpg|100px]]<br>[[File:Minato-mirai from Yamashita Park at night.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|2\n|[[Jakarta]]<ref>Various international sources limit their population estimates to DKI Jakarta itself (the national capital district). However, the urbanization of Jakarta extends into the regencies of [[Tangerang Regency|Tangerang]], [[Bekasi Regency|Bekasi]], [[Bogor Regency|Bogor]] and [[Karawang Regency|Karawang]] and the separate cities of [[Bekasi]], [[Depok]] and [[Bogor]]. Demographia continues to use the \"Jakarta\" name instead of [[Jabodetabek]] because of its familiarity.</ref>\n|Indonesia\n|22,000,000\n|2,720\n|8,500\n|F / B\n|[[File:Jakarta cityscape during night time, taken from 27th floor; 2013.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|3\n|[[Metro Manila|Manila]]<ref>The population is higher than other agglomeration estimates (such as the United Nations), tend to be limited to [[Metro Manila]], which is a province level jurisdiction. The continuous urbanization of Manila extends outward into [[Bulacan]], [[Cavite]], [[Laguna (province)|Laguna]], [[Rizal]] and [[Quezon]] provinces. The Demographia population estimate is a \"build-up\" of municipality population within the continuously developed area (urban area or agglomeration).</ref>\n|Philippines\n|20,795,000\n|1,425\n|14,600\n|C / B\n|[[File:Paco and San Andres Bukid with Ortigas skyline and Mandaluyong (aerial view) (Manila)(2018-02-20).jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|4\n|[[Seoul]]\u2013[[Incheon]]<ref>Includes satellite cities in [[Gyeonggi-do|Gyeonggi]] Province such as [[Suwon]], [[Goyang]], [[Seongnam]], [[Bucheon]] and [[Ansan]] which are treated as separate urban agglomerations by the United Nations.</ref>\n|South Korea\n|19,910,000\n|1,943\n|10,200\n|C / B\n|[[File:Seoul at night.jpg|100px]]<br>[[File:Icheon bridge.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|5\n|[[Shanghai]]\n|China\n|18,400,000\n|2,396\n|6,300\n|C / B\n|[[File:2012 Pudong.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n|6\n|[[Osaka]]\u2013[[Kobe]]\u2013[[Kyoto]]<ref>Includes [[Nara, Nara|Nara]] and [[Himeji]]. United Nations estimates separate Osaka\u2013Kobe and Kyoto and exclude both Nara and Himeji. Excludes urban area of [[\u014ctsu, Shiga|\u014ctsu]] (700,000; 389 km\u00b2).</ref>\n|Japan\n|17,320,000\n|2,720\n|5,300\n|C / B\n|[[File:Nakanoshima, Osaka in 201504.JPG|100px]]<br>[[File:Twilight view of Kobe,